    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-11T10:21:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-11T10:21:00-05:00" n="976"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d976">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 860d.00/287</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Helsingfors</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HT2"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Haynes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d976fn3">Sent via the Legation in Sweden (No. 2823).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Helsingfors</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-11T17:00:00+01:39">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 11, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received September 13, 3 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>90. Finnish delegation which has been in Germany some time searching for a king
                    has procured the assent of <persName corresp="#p_FC1">Frederick Carl</persName>
                    of Hesse who married Kaiser <persName corresp="#p_MWC1">Wilhelm</persName>’s
                    sister, Margarita, to accept the throne. Diet called to meet September 26 for
                    the election.</p>
                <pb facs="0901" n="811" xml:id="pg_811"/>
                <p>Finnish government and the Krupp firm have formed two-million-mark company to
                    investigate Finnish iron resources. This is another phase in Germany’s program
                    to exploit Finland commercially.</p>
                <p>Coat of arms of the British Consulate in Helsingfors has been painted in German
                    colors during the night of September 8. Finnish officials have apologized,
                    restored damaged shield, and are searching for the guilty parties. The press
                    deeply deplores the insult. I believe animosity against the present British
                    Consul who is greatly disliked personally was the real cause of the
                    incident.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HT2">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Haynes</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
